# Cursor Rules — Unity C# (2022.3+)

> Purpose: Make Cursor generate **compilable, editor-friendly, and performant** Unity C# code with minimal hand-fixing. Treat this as a living spec.

---

## 0) High‑Level Directives for Cursor

* **Target**: Unity 2022.3 LTS or later, .NET Standard 2.1 (or project default).
* **Code must compile** on first try in an empty project after creating folders below.
* **Prefer built‑ins** (Unity components/events, ScriptableObjects, Addressables, Input System) before custom systems.
* **Never add packages** silently; list them under *Packages* so a human can install.
* **No magic singletons** unless explicitly requested. Use DI-friendly patterns or service locators.
* **Avoid Update() churn**—prefer events, coroutines, InvokeRepeating, or Unity callbacks.
* **Use `Time.deltaTime` for time-based motion**; `Time.fixedDeltaTime` for physics; `Time.unscaledDeltaTime` when pausing/time manipulation is needed.
* **Cache components** in `Awake`/`Start`; avoid `GetComponent` in loops; use `TryGetComponent` when null is expected.
* **Guard editor-only APIs** with `#if UNITY_EDITOR` and `#endif`; ensure editor code never compiles in builds.
* **Separate runtime vs. editor scripts** in folders and with asmdefs.
* **Thread safety**: Unity APIs are main-thread only; document thread usage for async operations.

---

## 1) Default Project Structure

```
Assets/
  Scripts/
    Core/
    Gameplay/
    UI/
    Systems/
    Data/
    Editor/
  ScriptableObjects/
  Prefabs/
  Scenes/
  Settings/
```

* Create **assembly definitions** per top-level folder (`Core`, `Gameplay`, `UI`, `Systems`, `Editor`).
* `Editor` asmdef references runtime asmdefs and is marked `include platforms: Editor` only.

---

## 2) Coding Standards (C# + Unity)

* **Naming**: `PascalCase` for public members/types, `camelCase` for private fields; prefix private serialized fields with `[SerializeField] private`.
* **XML docs** on public APIs and ScriptableObject definitions; include `<param>` and `<returns>` tags.
* **Namespaces**: `Company.Product.Module` (e.g., `Acme.RPG.UI`); avoid deep nesting (max 3-4 levels).
* **Attributes**: Use `[Header]`, `[Tooltip]`, `[Range]`, `[Min]`, `[Max]`, `[SerializeField]` liberally for inspector clarity.
* **Unity Lifecycle**: Only implement used messages (`Awake`, `Start`, `OnEnable`, `OnDisable`, `OnDestroy`, `OnApplicationPause`, etc.).
* **Nullability**: enable nullable context in asmdef (`/nullable enable`) when possible; otherwise use defensive checks with null-conditional operators (`?.`, `??`).
* **Events**: prefer `UnityEvent` for inspector wiring; C# events (`Action`, `EventHandler`) for code-only; always unsubscribe in `OnDisable`/`OnDestroy`.
* **Coroutines**: Stop coroutines in `OnDisable` or `OnDestroy`; store `Coroutine` reference if stopping early.
* **Serialization**: Use `[SerializeField]` for private fields shown in inspector; `[HideInInspector]` to hide public fields; `[System.Serializable]` for nested classes/structs.
* **Logging**: Use `Debug.Log*` sparingly; gate noisy logs with a `bool verboseLogging` or compile symbol `DEV_LOGS`; use `Debug.LogWarning` for recoverable issues, `Debug.LogError` for critical failures.

---

## 3) Unity-Specific Patterns

* **ScriptableObjects** for data/config (stats, item defs, curve sets, input bindings). Provide `CreateAssetMenu` with clear menu paths.
* **Object Pooling** via `UnityEngine.Pool.ObjectPool<T>` or a simple pool component; dispose pools in `OnDestroy`.
* **Addressables** for dynamically loaded assets; expose labels in inspector; always release handles (`Release`/`ReleaseInstance`).
* **New Input System** (com.unity.inputsystem): generate `PlayerInput` actions; no legacy Input unless requested; use `InputAction.CallbackContext` for event-driven input.
* **Physics**: non-alloc queries (`RaycastNonAlloc`, `OverlapSphereNonAlloc`), `FixedUpdate` for forces, `Rigidbody.MovePosition/Rotation` for kinematic motion; prefer `Physics2D` for 2D games.
* **UI**: Use UI Toolkit when requested; otherwise Unity UI (uGUI). Avoid `Find()` at runtime; reference via inspector or use `GetComponentInParent`/`GetComponentInChildren` sparingly.
* **Scenes**: Use `SceneManager.LoadSceneAsync` with `allowSceneActivation` for loading screens; unload scenes with `UnloadSceneAsync` to free memory.
* **Timers**: Use `InvokeRepeating`/`Invoke` for simple delays; `Coroutine` with `WaitForSeconds`/`WaitForSecondsRealtime` for complex timing; `UniTask` (if package installed) for async timing.

---

## 4) Performance Checklist (apply before responding)

* ❏ No per-frame `GetComponent`/`FindObjectOfType`/`GameObject.Find`/`Transform.Find`.
* ❏ No LINQ/allocations in `Update`/`FixedUpdate`/hot paths; prefer `for` loops over `foreach` where possible.
* ❏ Use `List<T>.Clear()` and object reuse where appropriate; cache arrays/collections.
* ❏ Mark fields `readonly` when possible; use `const` for compile-time constants.
* ❏ Batch gizmo drawing behind `#if UNITY_EDITOR`; use `Gizmos.Draw*` sparingly.
* ❏ For heavy tasks, consider `C# Job System`/`Burst` (if scope allows) — otherwise note as future enhancement.
* ❏ Use `StringBuilder` for string concatenation in loops; avoid `string.Format` in hot paths.
* ❏ Cache `Camera.main` or reference via inspector; avoid repeated `Camera.main` calls.
* ❏ Use `CompareTag` instead of `tag == "string"` for performance.
* ❏ Prefer `SetActive(false)` over `Destroy` for temporary deactivation when objects will be reused.

---

## 5) Error Handling & State Safety

* **Guard nulls** for optional references; log meaningful errors once; use null-conditional operators (`?.`, `??`) where appropriate.
* **Lifecycle-safe**: unsubscribe in `OnDisable`; dispose in `OnDestroy`; check `this != null` before accessing in callbacks.
* **Coroutines**: check component enabled state before yield loops; handle `MonoBehaviour` destruction during coroutine execution.
* **Async**: If using `async`, avoid `Task.Run` for Unity APIs; use `await UniTask` (if package installed) or document that `await` is for non-Unity work; never await Unity APIs on background threads.
* **Validation**: Use `[Conditional("UNITY_EDITOR")]` for editor-only validation; validate `RequiredReference` attributes in `Awake`/`OnValidate`.
* **Exception handling**: Catch specific exceptions; log stack traces for debugging; avoid swallowing exceptions silently.

---

## 6) Testing & Validation

* Create **PlayMode tests** for behaviours relying on scene; **EditMode tests** for pure logic.
* Provide a minimal **Test Scene** under `Assets/Scenes/Tests` when adding a system.
* For algorithmic code, add an **EditMode** test with NUnit `[Test]`.

---

## 7) Packages (declare, don't auto-install)

* `com.unity.inputsystem` (Input System) — if player controls are required.
* `com.unity.addressables` — for dynamic asset loading.
* `com.unity.textmeshpro` — for UI text (preferred over Text component).
* `com.unity.test-framework` — for Edit/Play mode tests.
* Optional: 
  * `com.cysharp.unitask` for async patterns (better than `Task` for Unity).
  * `com.unity.collections`, `com.unity.jobs`, `com.unity.burst` for DOTS/Jobs when justified.
  * `com.unity.mathematics` for high-performance math (when Burst is used).
  * `com.unity.localization` for i18n support.
  * `com.unity.analytics` for analytics (if needed).

When a feature depends on a package, **list the package** at top of the response and gate sample code with `#if` directives or comments indicating package dependency.

---

## 8) Assembly Definitions (guidance)

* One asmdef per major folder; reference graph should be **acyclic** (Core → Gameplay/UI/Systems, not circular).
* Runtime asmdefs **must not** reference `Editor` asmdefs.
* Turn on **unsafe** only when strictly necessary; document why.
* Enable **override references** to include `Unity.InputSystem`, `Unity.Addressables`, etc. when needed.
* Set **API Compatibility Level** to `.NET Standard 2.1` (or match project settings).
* Enable **nullable reference types** (`/nullable enable`) in asmdef for better null safety.
* Use **Assembly Version** to control versioning if needed.

---

## 9) File Templates (Cursor should generate like this)

### 9.1 MonoBehaviour Component

```csharp
using UnityEngine;

namespace Acme.RPG.Gameplay
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Handles player movement using the new Input System.
    /// </summary>
    public sealed class PlayerMover : MonoBehaviour
    {
        [Header("Movement")]
        [SerializeField] private float moveSpeed = 5f;

        private CharacterController controller;
        private Vector3 velocity;

        private void Awake()
        {
            controller = GetComponent<CharacterController>();
        }

        private void Update()
        {
            // Input should be provided by another system or PlayerInput hook.
            Vector2 input = Vector2.zero; // TODO: inject or set from input layer
            Vector3 move = new Vector3(input.x, 0f, input.y);
            controller.Move(move * (moveSpeed * Time.deltaTime));
        }
    }
}
```

### 9.2 ScriptableObject Data

```csharp
using UnityEngine;

namespace Acme.RPG.Data
{
    [CreateAssetMenu(menuName = "Acme/Stats/CharacterStats", fileName = "CharacterStats")]
    public sealed class CharacterStats : ScriptableObject
    {
        [Min(1)] public int level = 1;
        [Min(0)] public float maxHealth = 100f;
        [Min(0)] public float attackPower = 10f;
    }
}
```

### 9.3 Object Pool (generic wrapper)

```csharp
using UnityEngine;
using UnityEngine.Pool;

namespace Acme.RPG.Core
{
    public sealed class PooledSpawner : MonoBehaviour
    {
        [SerializeField] private GameObject prefab;
        [SerializeField] private int defaultCapacity = 16;
        [SerializeField] private int maxSize = 128;

        private ObjectPool<GameObject> pool;

        private void Awake()
        {
            pool = new ObjectPool<GameObject>(
                createFunc: () => Instantiate(prefab),
                actionOnGet: go => go.SetActive(true),
                actionOnRelease: go => go.SetActive(false),
                actionOnDestroy: go => Destroy(go),
                collectionCheck: false, defaultCapacity, maxSize);
        }

        public GameObject Get() => pool.Get();
        public void Release(GameObject go) => pool.Release(go);
    }
}
```

---

## 10) Generation Heuristics & Review Checklist

When Cursor writes or edits code, it must include:

1. **Imports** (`using` statements) and **namespaces**.
2. **SerializeField** for inspector-tuned private fields.
3. Minimal **comments** describing intent; XML docs for public APIs.
4. **TODO hooks** where integration with input/UI/Addressables is expected.
5. **Editor guards** for tooling (`#if UNITY_EDITOR`).
6. An **example usage** (prefab setup or scene steps) in a short note.

**Self-check before finalizing**:

* ❏ Does it reference any package not listed?
* ❏ Does it use legacy Input? (avoid unless requested)
* ❏ Any Update loops doing work that could be event-driven?
* ❏ Are allocations avoided in hot paths?
* ❏ Are lifecycles (`OnEnable`/`OnDisable`) handling subscriptions?

---

## 11) Documentation & Comments

* Provide a short **README snippet** when adding a new system: purpose, setup steps, dependencies.
* Public classes/methods: XML docs summarizing behavior and parameters.

---

## 12) Editor Tooling (optional section Cursor may add)

* Place custom inspectors and editor windows under `Assets/Scripts/Editor` and `#if UNITY_EDITOR` guards.
* For inspectors, prefer `SerializedObject/SerializedProperty` to keep prefab overrides intact.
* Use `MenuItem` for tools; keep them deterministic and undo-friendly.

---

## 13) Scene & Prefab Guidance

* Keep **prefabs** small and composable; avoid deep nesting.
* Expose key references via inspector; avoid `Find` calls at runtime.
* Provide **sample prefab** setup instructions when introducing components.

---

## 14) CI & Warnings

* Treat compiler warnings as errors in CI (if present); locally, keep zero warnings in new code.
* Avoid API marked `[Obsolete]` unless migration is impossible—document rationale.

---

## 15) PR / Diff Expectations (for AI-generated changes)

* Summarize intent of change and testing steps.
* Note any new assets, scenes, or packages to add.
* If refactor touches multiple files, include a **migration note** (e.g., renames, namespace moves).

---

## 16) Request Formats (how to ask Cursor)

* **Create a component**: "Create `HealthSystem` MonoBehaviour in `Acme.RPG.Gameplay`, with `[SerializeField]` maxHealth, currentHealth; public `TakeDamage(float)`, `Heal(float)`, UnityEvents `OnDamaged`, `OnDied`. Include sample prefab setup."
* **Make a ScriptableObject**: "Create `DamageType` SO with enum + multiplier map; add CreateAssetMenu."
* **Add pooling**: "Wrap projectile prefab with pooled spawner and sample fire method; no Update polling—use event trigger."
* **Editor tool**: "Custom inspector for `Quest` SO with reorderable steps; `#if UNITY_EDITOR`."

---

## 17) Non‑Goals (what not to do by default)

* **No paid/licensed Asset Store assets in git** — paths in `config/paid-assets.local-only.txt` are local-only; never stage, commit, or push them. See `docs/PAID_ASSETS.md` and run `python3 scripts/check_paid_assets.py` before commits.
* No hidden global singletons or static state holding scene references.
* No Resources folder reliance (prefer Addressables or direct references).
* No heavy reflection or runtime codegen.
* No blocking I/O on main thread (use `async`/`await` or coroutines).
* No `MonoBehaviour.Update()` for polling (use events or coroutines).
* No `GameObject.Find()` or `FindObjectOfType()` at runtime (use inspector references).
* No `SendMessage`/`BroadcastMessage` (use events or direct references).

---

## 18) Quick Snippet: Event-Driven Tick

```csharp
public interface ITickable { void Tick(float dt); }
// A central driver can call Tick on registered systems from one Update loop.
```

---

## 19) Additional Best Practices

* **Structs vs Classes**: Use structs for small, value-type data (Vector3, Color, etc.); classes for larger objects with identity.
* **IDisposable**: Implement `IDisposable` for types holding native resources (e.g., Addressable handles); dispose in `OnDestroy`.
* **Attributes**: Use `[RequireComponent]` to ensure dependencies; `[DisallowMultipleComponent]` for singleton-like components.
* **Prefab Variants**: Prefer prefab variants over prefab nesting for composition.
* **Scene Management**: Use additive scene loading for modular level design; avoid loading/unloading entire scenes frequently.
* **Profiling**: Add `Profiler.BeginSample`/`EndSample` blocks for custom profiling markers in development builds.

---

**End of rules. Keep responses concise but complete; include setup steps and any required asmdef/package notes.**
